# Repo-root environment discovery (BimRoss)

## Convention

- **Tracked:** **`.env.example`** at the **repository root** (unless the repo genuinely has no env-driven behavior—e.g. pure static docs).
- **Gitignored:** **`.env`**, **`.env.dev`**, **`.env.prod`** (and common variants like **`.env.local`**) containing real secrets; never commit keys, tokens, or kubeconfigs.
- **Dual environments (dev + prod):** Repos that run both **local/test** and **production** should use **`.env.dev`** and **`.env.prod`** (both gitignored), with **`.env.example`** as the committed template. **`./scripts/use-env.sh dev|prod`** symlinks **`.env`** → **`.env.dev`** or **`.env.prod`** so `docker compose`, `godotenv`, and tools that only read **`.env`** pick up the right mode—same pattern as **employee-factory**, **slack-orchestrator**, **makeacompany-ai**, and **stripe-factory**. Cluster/runtime pushes (e.g. **`scripts/update-rancher-secrets.sh`**) should source **`.env.prod`** only (makeacompany-ai defaults to **`.env.prod`** when that file exists).
- **Purpose:** Operators and agents see **one obvious place** for “what variables exist” when the repo is open in Cursor or the BimRoss multi-root workspace—without opening Kubernetes or GitHub first.

## What to put in `.env.example`

- **Names** of all variables the app, scripts, or Terraform expect, with **short comments** pointing to where values come from (e.g. “Stripe Dashboard → Developers → API keys”, “`gh secret set`”, “Rancher”).
- **No real secrets**—use empty values, `sk_test_...` placeholders, or obvious placeholders.

## Stripe / stripe-factory

- **`STRIPE_API_KEY_TEST`** and similar names refer to the Stripe **Dashboard secret key** for the right mode (`sk_test_…` / `sk_live_…`), not something generated inside **`stripe-factory`**. The factory repo versions **catalog** (Terraform); keys always come from Stripe (or GitHub Actions secrets for CI).

## Admin cluster: `scripts/update-rancher-secrets.sh`

Repos that push **runtime secrets** to the **admin** Kubernetes cluster (not GitOps plaintext) should expose a **single** script at **`scripts/update-rancher-secrets.sh`**:

- **Name is stable** across BimRoss repos so operators always know what to run.
- **Behavior is repo-specific**: e.g. **stripe-factory** and **makeacompany-ai** apply `makeacompany-ai-runtime-secrets` in namespace `makeacompany-ai`; **employee-factory** delegates to the existing Slack/LLM sync; **cookie-monster** delegates to `sync-twitter-worker-secrets.sh`.
- Repos with **no** cluster secrets may ship a **no-op** script that prints where to go instead (**rancher-admin** exits non-zero with pointers; some stubs exit 0 with a message).

Kubeconfig: scripts typically default **`KUBECONFIG`** to **`~/.kube/config/admin.yaml`** (fallback **`grant-admin.yaml`**) when unset—see **`bimross-kubeconfig-contexts.mdc`**.

## When bootstrapping a new repo

See **`bimross-new-repo-bootstrap.mdc`**: add **`.env.example`** early in the same change that introduces scripts, Compose, or backends that read env. If the service needs cluster runtime secrets, add **`scripts/update-rancher-secrets.sh`** in the same PR or follow-up.
